  - Why: a malformed or unreviewed amendment can silently affect whitelist behavior, while spec/acceptance/eval_protocol amendments are not enforced at all. The amendment system is still partly aspirational.
  - Classification: Blocker via REG §5.1 contract immutability / operator-layer drift.
  - Fix: either implement amendment validation/regeneration, or narrow REGULATION to the currently enforced minimum. Recommended: add `validate_amendments(lock, round_dir)` checking file exists, sha matches lock, `target/supersedes/meeting` present, meeting exists and is decided, target is one of base files; make missing/invalid amendment a blocker. Defer effective regeneration if needed, but remove the claim until implemented.
  - Protocol: routine amendment.

- item 3: `context_harness/operator/REGULATION.md:97,119-125`; `context_harness/operator/OPERATOR.md:66-72`; `harness/check_operator_round.py:593-641`
  - What: new close-subcommand gap. Docs say `close <round>` transitions only if all Gates 1-5 pass. The checker’s `cmd_close` only calls `cmd_gates`, and `cmd_gates` is Gate 5 process integrity only. It does not validate Gate 1 build/test, Gate 2 reports, Gate 3 cross-agreement, or Gate 4 process metrics.
  - Why: the lock can be closed even if build/tests were never run or evaluator reports are missing, as long as Gate 5 passes. That makes “closed” overclaim round quality.
  - Classification: Blocker via REG §5.1 checker/gate reliability and operator-layer contradiction.
  - Fix: either rename/scope `close` as “Gate 5 close only” and require external evidence fields, or add lock/contract fields for `gate1..gate4` evidence and have `close` refuse unless those are present and pass. Minimal fix: require a `gate_status.json` or `acceptance.md` evidence section referenced by lock before close.
  - Protocol: routine amendment; no architectural rethink.

- item 4: `harness/check_operator_round.py:515-569`; `context_harness/operator/PROCESS_AUDIT_CHECKLIST.md:12`; `context_harness/operator/REGULATION.md:129-130`
  - What: new commit-traceability logic is incomplete and has matching bugs.
  - Why:
    - It uses `git diff --name-only base..HEAD`, so uncommitted working-tree changes are ignored.
    - It does not verify commit timestamps against `started_at`/`closed_at`, despite PROCESS_AUDIT saying that is the criterion.
    - It does not map commits to the lock/process-log; it only checks touched paths.
    - The `/*` matcher is effectively wrong: for `docs/*`, `docs/a.md` contains `/` in the tested suffix and will not match. This creates false positives.
    - `/**` uses `pat[:-3]`, so `foo/**` becomes prefix `foo`, which can overmatch `foobar/...`.
    - Common patterns like `workspace/ios/**/*.swift` are not supported.
  - Classification: Blocker via REG §5.1 “Any commit in this round not traceable to a contract lock.”
  - Fix: use `fnmatch.fnmatchcase` or `pathlib.PurePosixPath.match` for whitelist patterns; include dirty tree via `git diff --name-only base` or separately check `git diff --name-only` and `git diff --cached --name-only`; either implement timestamp/process-log mapping or amend checklist language to “diff since base_commit.”
  - Protocol: routine amendment.

- item 5: `harness/check_operator_round.py:456-463,572-580`; `context_harness/operator/REGULATION.md:98`
  - What: new live-pointer hash check under-blocks malformed pointer files. REG says `lint_config.txt` and `convention_version.txt` contain `<path>\n<sha256>` and mismatch is a blocker. Checker treats malformed or missing two-line format as an advisory and skips the live hash check.
  - Why: a bad pointer file disables the exact protection v5.1 added. A round could close without active lint/convention hash enforcement.
  - Classification: Blocker via REG §5.1 lock hash / lint hash reliability.
  - Fix: malformed pointer format should be a blocker. Also validate format during `lock <round_id>`, not only at `gates`.
  - Protocol: routine amendment.

- item 6: `context_harness/operator/REGULATION.md:156-170`; `harness/check_operator_round.py:346-431`
  - What: residual audit overclaim. REG §7 still promises role matrix consistency and `stages_completed` performer/cross-validator validation. Checker does not validate role assignments, human cross-validator stages, or `stages_completed` entries against expected performer/reviewer evidence.
  - Why: a lock can claim stages completed without the expected cross-validation actually happening. That is central to v5’s governance model.
  - Classification: Blocker via REG §5.1 operator-layer drift audit.
  - Fix: add a stage matrix table in machine-readable config or parse STAGE_CONTRACT rows; validate every `lock.stages_completed[]` has corresponding decided meeting/artifact and expected performer/cross-validator. If not implementing now, remove that claim from REG §7.
  - Protocol: routine amendment.

